    pearls: ["Every new symptom in an older adult should be considered a drug side effect until proven otherwise — this prevents prescribing cascades","The prescribing cascade is the most preventable form of polypharmacy: NSAID → hypertension → amlodipine → edema → furosemide → hypokalemia → potassium supplement → GI upset → PPI","Anticholinergic burden is cumulative — a patient on low-dose oxybutynin, diphenhydramine, and amitriptyline may have a combined anticholinergic burden equivalent to severe toxicity","Beers Criteria medications to memorize: benzodiazepines, first-generation antihistamines, TCAs, long-acting sulfonylureas, meperidine, and non-COX-2 selective NSAIDs — all avoid in elderly","Time-to-benefit analysis: statins take 2-5 years to prevent cardiovascular events; bisphosphonates take 1-3 years for fracture reduction — deprescribe if life expectancy is shorter than time-to-benefit","Deprescribing is a clinical intervention, not simply stopping medications — it requires a systematic approach: taper schedule, monitoring plan, patient education, and follow-up"],
