    diagnostics: ["ESR (erythrocyte sedimentation rate): typically markedly elevated > 50 mm/hr (often > 100 mm/hr); normal ESR does NOT exclude GCA (10-15% have normal ESR)","CRP (C-reactive protein): elevated, often > 2.5 mg/dL; more sensitive than ESR and less affected by age and anemia","Temporal artery biopsy (TAB): gold standard for diagnosis; shows transmural granulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells, intimal hyperplasia, and fragmented internal elastic lamina; minimum 2 cm specimen required due to skip lesions","Temporal artery ultrasound (color duplex): 'halo sign' (dark hypoechoic halo around the vessel lumen) suggests arterial wall edema — can help guide biopsy or serve as initial non-invasive test","CBC: normocytic anemia of chronic inflammation, thrombocytosis (reactive) are common findings","LFTs: alkaline phosphatase elevation occurs in up to 30% of GCA patients (hepatic arteritis)","Ophthalmologic examination: fundoscopy to evaluate for anterior ischemic optic neuropathy (AION) — pale, swollen optic disc with cotton-wool spots"],
